Not long after the People Magazine article I received a call from David Hackworth on the telephone.  I felt honored.<br>
He was a Wolfhound (27th Infantry) in the Korean War while my experiences as a Wolfhound was in Vietnam.  We had a pleasant conversation on the telephone.  Two of the points he made in his book About Face were military training and preparedness and ticket punching.<br><br>
I knew officers who punched their tickets and officers who did not.  Didn't we all?  I don't recall a time, when I as a soldier, didn't get all that I asked for.  Ask MTF how many times he came in, when he didn't have to, and don't let him be modest.  I believe that the problems that exist in the world exist less in the military.  I could be wrong.<br><br>
I met Colonel Millet at a reunion.  He is a recipient of the Congressional Medal of Honor and has a wonderful sense of humor.  I was told that Colonels Hackworth and Millet had been at the same place at the same time in Korea and remembered it quite differently.  <br><br>
Cook, you are quite right, speaking about the power of small units.  There effectiveness, mental and physical, was the key to success -- along with a little help from MTF, Art and all the rest.<br><br>
Truth is the first casualty of war -- sure I'll buy that.   I was a dead man's replacement for Operation Attleboro near Tay Ninh, (MTF -- you might remember that -- Nov. 5, &quot;66&quot;)  There were two Congressional Medals of Honor awarded -- one posthumously.  One to an officer -- one to an enlisted man.  They were both earned by good men, or so I was told.  That is truth, perception withstanding.  <br><br>
Ooops, got carrried away again.  I believe both colonels to be honorable men.  Perception is tainted/tinted by both pride and pain -- both part of war.<br><br>
Paul
